As concerns increase around Coronavirus (Covid-19) globally, the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) has urged Nigerians to trust information only from verified sources. In a statement, made available to LEADERSHIP, UNICEF said it has become aware of messages being circulated that are being falsely attributed to the organization and stressed that all genuine information can be found on its website, including information on how to protect oneself and loved ones from the virus. People can also visit the World Health Organisation (WHO) website for further updated information, the organisation added. It said UNICEF, in collaboration with WHO, is supporting the Nigerian government’s response to the outbreak. “UNICEF is leading on preventative actions in communities with risk communication, providing hygiene and medical kits to schools and health clinics and monitoring the impact of the outbreak to support continuity of care, education and social services,” it added. In the same vein, the Lagos state commissioner for health, prof. Akin Abayomi has also appealed to residents to stop coming up or sharing fake news and misinformation about suspected cases of COVID-19 as its drained resources and energy that should be deployed in checking the spread of real cases. Abayomi added that the medical team was wasting a lot of energy on fake news, as it took a lot of man power because the team usually would investigate the suspected cases mentioned on social media. 